        <td bgcolor="black" colspan="2"  valign="top">
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/30/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 02:12:02</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=2137"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
 
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=2137')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=TopicQuote&amp;TOPIC_ID=5586&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=OT%3A+English+as+the+official+language+of+California"><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"> This thread is off-topic.  You can tell by the OT in the heading.  Board Moderators feel free to nuke it if you wish =).  If yer not a board operator, don't bitch about having to read it because you don't. ;)</P><P>That other long ass thread had some Canadians whining in it about how the U.S. was going to have to start using other languages, seemingly unaware that our Drivers Handbooks are already printed in like 10 different languages (how many are yours done in, eh?).</P><P>As I stumbled through the thread, and the alcohol started to numb my senses, I kept thinking to myself someone will probably bring up this point (and maybe they did, but as I said, the alcohol has started to numb my senses :p )...</P><P>The Bill of Rights, which everyone had a grand time trying to interpret in that Other Thread, doesn't really have that many words.  It's not that hard to read.  Let's look at the last one, Amendment X (or 10 to the public school crowd):</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>The powers not delegated to the United States by the Constitution, nor prohibited by it to the states, are reserved to the states respectively, or to the people. <hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Now, I'm not a constitutional lawyer, nor do I play one on TV.  But I don't remember seeing anywhere in it that the issue of an official language was discussed...  That would lead me to believe it was a State's rights issue (or the people, how the hell is that supposed to be decided?).</P><P>Welllllll, just point your little browser over to the California State's Legal Info web site at the State Constitution, Article 3 in particular... <a href="http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/.const/.article_3" target="_blank">http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/.const/.article_3</a> (see that .ca.gov in the domain?  Yes, that's the California Government).  Scroll on down to Section 6.</P><P>Here it is in whole for you to lazy to right click and open a new window...</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>SEC. 6.  (a) Purpose.<BR>   English is the common language of the people of the United States<BR>of America and the State of California.  This section is intended to<BR>preserve, protect and strengthen the English language, and not to<BR>supersede any of the rights guaranteed to the people by this<BR>Constitution.<BR>   (b) English as the Official Language of California.<BR> English is the official language of the State of California.<BR>   (c) Enforcement.<BR>   The Legislature shall enforce this section by appropriate<BR>legislation.  The Legislature and officials of the State of<BR>California shall take all steps necessary to insure that the role of<BR>English as the common language of the State of California is<BR>preserved and enhanced.  The Legislature shall make no law which<BR>diminishes or ignores the role of English as the common language of<BR>the State of California.<BR>   (d) Personal Right of Action and Jurisdiction of Courts.<BR>   Any person who is a resident of or doing business in the State of<BR>California shall have standing to sue the State of California to<BR>enforce this section, and the Courts of record of the State of<BR>California shall have jurisdiction to hear cases brought to enforce<BR>this section.  The Legislature may provide reasonable and appropriate<BR>limitations on the time and manner of suits brought under this<BR>section.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Hrmm, wouldn't it be interesting if the state legislator's all had to read this before they ran for office?  I found part D to be really interesting, I wonder why we don't hear about people bringing suit to enforce the part about promoting english (preserved and ENHANCED).</P><P>To be honest, most people don't know the U.S. Constitution well, let alone their own state's.  But you'd think someone on the right (and yes, I am a conservative, Christian republican) would challenge all these state funded uses (which as I understand it, have to be passed into law as a budget) which would clearly diminish English as the primary language.</P><P>Just some food for thought, now argue amongst yourselves!</P><P>Lykos D'Lich</P><P>ObNecro: Anyone have any good necro skins for the new UI yet?</P><P> </font></td>

      </tr>

